  [1mWhy[22m [1mthe[22m [1msymptom[22m [1m"first[22m [1mclick[22m [1mfails,[22m [1msecond[22m [1mworks"[22m[K
[K
  Strongly suggests [1mtiming[22m [1m/[22m [1mlazy-load[22m: on first click [38;2;177;185;249mdashboardBlock.DataSelector [mis null, silent-return fires (line 1183-1187), no UI feedback.  
  On second click, state is populated. I can't confirm without live repro which field is null and why it's populated the second time.[K
[K
  [1mOptions[22m[K
[K
  [1m(a)[22m [1mSpeculative[22m [1mhardening[22m [1mcommit[22m [1m(what[22m [1mI'd[22m [1mdo)[22m: turn every silent-return into a user-visible error, add null guards, and log enough context that 
  the next user to hit this can tell us exactly which null was the problem. Doesn't guarantee the fix, but guarantees the next report has a        
  diagnostic trail.[K
[K
  [1m(b)[22m [1mDefer[22m [1muntil[22m [1mrepro[22m: ask for a browser-console screenshot / network trace when the user hits the first-click-fails state. Clean, but blocks us 
  until someone collects it.[K
[K
  [1m(c)[22m [1mLive[22m [1mPlaywright[22m [1mtest[22m: I can automate "open dashboard → add likelihood panel" and capture server log + screenshot when nothing appears on the 
  dashboard. 30-40 min investment. No guarantee the bug reproduces in an automated flow (might need human rhythm).[K
[K
  [1mMy[22m [1mpick:[22m [1m(a).[22m Hardening changes are small, low-risk, and even if they don't fully fix the symptom they make the [3mnext[23m occurrence diagnosable.     
  That's strictly better than the current silent-failure.[K
